  <!-- About Section -->
<div class="w3-main" style="margin-left:50px">
  <div class="w3-container w3-padding-32" id="about">
    <h1 class="w3-border-light-grey w3-padding-16">about</h1>
   	<h3>Old Lithuanian</h3>
	<h5>is attested from the 16th century onwards. It is similar to the modern language, and many of its peculiarities can still be found today in modern dialects (see <a href="#introduction"><b>introduction</b></a>).
	The language has a complex accent system (see <a href="#sounds"><b>sounds</b></a>) which is actually transmitted in early writings. It has a dual, so-called postpositive local cases and, most remarkably, many athematic verbs (see <a href="#words"><b>words</b></a>).
	The syntax of Old and Modern Lithuanian is remarkable for absolute constructions and the modus relativus, a verbal mood for expressing indirect speech and propositional attitudes formed with participles (see <a href="#structures"><b>structures</b></a>).
	</h5><br>

	<h3>Lecturers</h3>
		<h4><a href="http://titus.uni-frankfurt.de/personal/gelumbec.html", target="_blank">Jolanta Gelumbeckaitė</a></h4>
		<p class="w3-opacity">University of Frankfurt</p>
		<h4><a href="https://www.flf.vu.lt/institutai/bkki/darbuotojai/94-lt/struktura/institutai/bkki/bk/928-jurgis-pakerys", target="_blank">Jurgis Pakerys</a></h4>
		<p class="w3-opacity">Vilnius University</p>
  </div>

